<h2>Solar Panels in California</h2>

<h3>Solar Resource and Production</h3>
<p>California's exceptional solar irradiance levels make it one of the premier locations globally for photovoltaic energy production. The state receives between 4.5-7.0 kWh/m¬≤/day of solar irradiance depending on location, with southern regions like Imperial County and the Mojave Desert achieving some of the highest levels in North America. Coastal areas, while experiencing some marine layer effects during morning hours, still maintain excellent production levels with the benefit of cooler temperatures that actually improve panel efficiency.</p>

<p>A typical 6kW residential solar system in California can produce between 9,000-11,000 kWh annually, often covering 80-100% of average household electricity consumption. Seasonal variations show peak production during spring and summer months (May through September), with winter production typically 60-70% of peak levels. However, the state's mild winters mean that even December and January maintain respectable production levels compared to northern states. The tilt angle and orientation of panels significantly impact production, with south-facing systems at 30-35¬∞ tilt achieving optimal year-round performance.</p>

